Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Solving the Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger Equation for a Particle in a Box", \
"Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8074594324828715`*^9, 3.8074594487922525`*^9}, {
  3.8076177444720974`*^9, 3.8076177502095847`*^9}, {3.8076315419037385`*^9, 
  3.8076315442771745`*^9}, {3.8076317240690165`*^9, 3.8076317343277235`*^9}, {
  3.8079650185938416`*^9, 3.8079650467347217`*^9}, {3.807978762083801*^9, 
  3.8079787666501837`*^9}, {3.80805592367854*^9, 3.8080559505599174`*^9}, {
  3.8087416220486813`*^9, 
  3.8087416446879406`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f5bd6680-2740-4d37-bb94-\
9cddbe2b4100"],

Cell["\<\
It turns out that there are only a few relevant problems for which the Schr\
\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation can be solved exactly (meaning we can write out \
an answer by working through some calculus and algebra). For more complex \
systems, we have to resort to numerical methods.  Nevertheless, working \
through these problems helps us illustrate many central concepts that are \
also relevant for more complex systems.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8087417074423857`*^9, 3.8087417258323154`*^9}, {
  3.808741782166544*^9, 3.808741784441101*^9}, {3.8087419590565305`*^9, 
  3.8087420095212*^9}, {3.808742053298977*^9, 3.8087421820291457`*^9}, {
  3.9156382955272408`*^9, 
  3.915638352880762*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"efea6788-ebc2-4748-b588-\
263a381828aa"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Particle in a One-Dimensional Box", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.808741664724339*^9, 
  3.808741693707781*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"643fb895-506e-4b9a-9f4b-\
481829e1e588"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The problem of a particle in a one-dimensional \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]box\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] (which is actually a line) involves a particle of \
mass ",
 StyleBox["m",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " that is constrained to the ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-axis between ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 0 and ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". We say that the particle is \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]free\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] in this region, meaning that it experiences no \
potential energy. We communicate this statement mathematically by writing \
that ",
 StyleBox["V",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " ) = 0 between ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = 0 and ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". To make sure the particle is in fact constrained, we state that the \
potential energy outside of this region is infinite, so ",
 StyleBox["V",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " ) = \[Infinity]. We can visualize the potential energy as shown below:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8087422422543*^9, 3.80874232796352*^9}, {
  3.808742364055952*^9, 3.8087424345586123`*^9}, {3.8087425431948495`*^9, 
  3.808742740459358*^9}, {3.808742828336424*^9, 
  3.8087428363459044`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f09c0193-d3f5-4e0a-9b26-\
047c7b167427"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{"V", 
    RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}]}],
   FontSlant->"Italic"], 
  StyleBox["=",
   FontSlant->"Plain"], 
  TagBox[GridBox[{
     {"\[Piecewise]", GridBox[{
        {"0", 
         RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
          StyleBox["x",
           FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[LessEqual]", 
          StyleBox["a",
           FontSlant->"Plain"]}]},
        {"\[Infinity]", "otherwise"}
       },
       AllowedDimensions->{2, Automatic},
       Editable->True,
       GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
       GridBoxItemSize->{"Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{1.}}},
       GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
           Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
            Offset[0.84]}, 
