Cell["the average value of the momentum is also zero,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809354529403815*^9, 
  3.809354541022209*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dcb40edb-c8ec-4f7b-95fe-\
1ed658bf9232"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"<", 
   StyleBox["p",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], ">"}], " ", "=", " ", 
  "0"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809354547060335*^9, 
  3.809354554334771*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"62bdf85c-321a-4221-8a5f-\
68035707edb8"],

Cell["\<\
Conceptually, thinking about the momentum as telling us about which direction \
the particle is moving, we can say that the particle is equally likely to be \
moving in either direction.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809354696981162*^9, 
  3.809354743477193*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c05b411d-c186-495f-9a18-\
3daea08213c6"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Variance and the Uncertainty Principle", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.808751767178835*^9, 3.8087517800272408`*^9}, {
  3.808751811720478*^9, 
  3.808751818574256*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"86cbab4c-768a-464a-a5b7-\
1cf9aabd5b57"],

Cell["\<\
In lesson 03, we discussed the Heisenberg uncertainty principle in terms of \
the standard deviation of momentum and position,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809354758893871*^9, 3.8093547937523108`*^9}, {
  3.915643413743058*^9, 3.915643414831853*^9}, {3.9350742572557983`*^9, 
  3.935074257933792*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3a9a183e-dd6c-4644-bf8b-\
a89df48c0ba4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]", 
    StyleBox["x",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CapitalDelta]", 
    StyleBox["p",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]}]], "\[GreaterEqual]", 
  FractionBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.807624977916951*^9, 
  3.8076250410256267`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"60d5f07d-7b24-41e7-aa39-\
b9e4ffe4d13a"],

Cell["or, more formally,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8093548097710543`*^9, 
  3.809354811548803*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b52fed51-a7c4-4137-9a3f-\
225e58a542af"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", 
    StyleBox["x",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", 
    StyleBox["p",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]]}], "\[GreaterEqual]", 
  FractionBox["\[HBar]", "2"]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.807624977916951*^9, 3.8076250410256267`*^9}, {
  3.809354834124029*^9, 
  3.809354853595561*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7c8b894b-4155-4b67-8953-\
9b17be8607d8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In that lesson, we discussed the standard deviation in the form of its \
statistical definition for a number of measurements. However, the standard \
deviation can also be defined in terms of expectation values. For a variable ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", the variance (square of the standard deviation) can be written as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809354871915944*^9, 3.8093549630547757`*^9}, {
  3.809355203580864*^9, 
  3.809355205769622*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a4ba1e99-a160-4a9d-84c4-\
d83e19c237c1"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", 
   StyleBox["x",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["x",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "-", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", 
     StyleBox["x",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], 
    "2"]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.807624977916951*^9, 3.8076250410256267`*^9}, {
  3.809354834124029*^9, 3.809354853595561*^9}, {3.8093549712866077`*^9, 
  3.809355022104103*^9}, {3.8093550881611676`*^9, 
  3.80935511848426*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1a92c53b-1d1a-420c-83d1-\
0cc6a3c72899"],

Cell["\<\
In other words, it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s the mean square minus the square of the \
mean. We can validate the Heisenberg uncertainty principle for the particle \
in a box using this formulation.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8093551348384733`*^9, 3.809355174353034*^9}, {
  3.915813534750822*^9, 3.915813560934507*^9}, {3.9350744006037216`*^9, 
  3.935074425638462*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c88857fb-d130-4c23-a480-\
0040f395ecf0"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Application of the Particle in a Box", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8087518549039154`*^9, 
  3.8087518600335894`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c9c0dae4-8021-4191-acfc-\
19e2ce1535e6"],

Cell["\<\
We have thus far used the model of a particle in a box to illustrate how we \
can apply the postulates of quantum mechanics to interpret systems described \
by the Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation. However, we can apply it as a \
simplistic model to interpret the properties of certain molecules. \
Specifically, the particle-in-a-box system can act as a model for the \[Pi] \
electrons in linear conjugated hydrocarbons.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809358742727098*^9, 
  3.809358857886154*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"639774ab-2ade-4859-bbae-\
760c54fddc39"],

Cell["Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s take the example of butadiene,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809358900527711*^9, 3.809358905411962*^9}, 
   3.8093591754863205`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"4ccecf9d-ab9d-46d6-8b6e-\
7a1a500a6424"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"m", "=", 
   RowBox[{"Molecule", "[", "\"\<Butadiene\>\"", "]"}]}], 
  ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"MoleculePlot", "[", "m", "]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"MoleculePlot3D", "[", 
  RowBox[{"m", ",", 
   RowBox[{"PlotTheme", "\[Rule]", "\"\<BallAndStick\>\""}]}], 
  "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellOpen->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8093589264760337`*^9, 3.8093589317089367`*^9}, {
  3.8093590122086177`*^9, 3.80935902283035*^9}, {3.8093590659773607`*^9, 
  3.8093590857940054`*^9}},
